==Season summary==
The [[1957–58 in English football|1957–58 season]] was West Ham's nineteenth season in the [[Football League Second Division|Second Division]] since their relegation in [[1931–32 West Ham United F.C. season|season 1931–32]]. The club were managed by [[Ted Fenton]] and the team captain was [[Noel Cantwell]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/honours-55.html | title=Ted Fenton | publisher=www.leaguemanagers.com | accessdate=24 April 2014 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140427010918/http://www.leaguemanagers.com/managers/honours-55.html | archivedate=27 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.independent.ie/unsorted/migration/noel-cantwell-26212550.html | title=Noel Cantwell | work=www.independent.ie | accessdate=24 April 2014}}</ref>

The season started badly for West Ham with only three wins from their first 10 games. However, after September 1957 they lost only three games hitting the first place in the league on 18 January 1958. They were in first place for all but one week until the end of the season as they finished as champions.<ref name=whustats/>  [[John Dick (footballer born 1930)|John Dick]] was the top scorer with 26 goals in all competitions and 21 in the league. The next highest scorer was [[Vic Keeble]] with 24. Dick and [[Ken Brown (footballer)|Ken Brown]] made the most appearances; 48 in all competitions.<ref name=whustats/> West Ham made the fifth round of the FA Cup before being eliminated 3-2 by [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]].

The season saw the last West Ham appearance for future football manager [[Malcolm Allison]] who had to retire following the removal of a lung after contracting [[tuberculosis]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/oct/15/malcolm-allison-obituary | title=Malcolm Allison obituary | work=The Guardian | date=15 October 2010 | accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> It also saw the first appearance by [[1965 European Cup Winners' Cup Final|1965 Cup Winners' Cup]] winner, [[Joe Kirkup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.westhamstats.info/westham.php?west=2&ham=387&united=Joe_Kirkup | title=Welcome to the Wonderful World of West Ham United Statistics&nbsp;— Joe Kirkup | publisher=www.westhamstats.info | accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref> In this season, West Ham created a player of the season award, the [[West Ham United F.C.#Hammer of the Year|Hammer of the Year award]]. The first winner was [[Andy Malcolm]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20140103/andy-malcolm-1933-2013_2236884_3600869 |title=Andy Malcolm |publisher=www.whufc.com |accessdate=24 April 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140106082124/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20140103/andy-malcolm-1933-2013_2236884_3600869 |archivedate=6 January 2014 |df= }}</ref> This season also saw the club break its record for the biggest victory. On 8 March 1958 they beat [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]], 8-0 with John Dick scoring four goals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.whufc.com/articles/20130308/on-this-day-8-march_2236884_3099606 | title=On this day 8 March | publisher=www.whufc.com | accessdate=24 April 2014 | deadurl=yes | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140426234734/http://www.whufc.com/articles/20130308/on-this-day-8-march_2236884_3099606 | archivedate=26 April 2014 | df=dmy-all }}</ref>

